  "text": "The diversity-based starting methods constitute an elaboration of an approach suggested in [CITATION_1] which may be formulated in the present context by viewing N as the set from which to create a subset N(K) of k elements. In this setting, the approach may be described as starting with an arbitrary seed element from N as the first element of N(K) and then sequentially selecting each of the remaining k -1 elements to maximize its minimum distance from the elements chosen so far. We first depict a simple instance of this method based on the following terminology. Let Ho = {i(h): h = 1, …, ko} denote the set of starting points selected as of iteration ko, where ko ranges from 1 to k. As the points i(h) are successively selected from N and added to Ho, we also refer to the set Io = N \\ Ho which identifies the points remaining in N as candidates to be selected for inclusion in Ho on the next iteration.",
